b. Hypermorphic Beta Function
The classical Beta function is defined as:
B(x,y)=Î“(x)Î“(y)Î“(x+y)B(x, y) = \frac{\Gamma(x) \Gamma(y)}{\Gamma(x + y)}B(x,y)=Î“(x+y)Î“(x)Î“(y)â€‹
Hypermorphic Adaptation:
BHM(x,y)=(Î“HM(x)â‹…Î“HM(y)Î“HM(x+y))modâ€‰â€‰Ïˆ(current precision)B_{\text{HM}}(x, y) = \left( \frac{\Gamma_{\text{HM}}(x) \cdot \Gamma_{\text{HM}}(y)}{\Gamma_{\text{HM}}(x + y)} \right) \mod \psi(\text{current precision})BHMâ€‹(x,y)=(Î“HMâ€‹(x+y)Î“HMâ€‹(x)â‹…Î“HMâ€‹(y)â€‹)modÏˆ(current precision)
Implementation:
python
Copy code
   def beta(self, other):
        """
        Calculates the hypermorphic Beta function B(x, y) of the current HyperMorphicNumber and another.
        
        Parameters:
            other (HyperMorphicNumber): The second argument of the Beta function.
        
        Returns:
            HyperMorphicNumber: The Beta function value, modulated by psi.
        """
        if not isinstance(other, HyperMorphicNumber):
            raise TypeError("Beta function requires two HyperMorphicNumber instances.")
        
        gamma_x = self.gamma()
        gamma_y = other.gamma()
        gamma_sum = (self + other).gamma()
        
        # Compute B(x, y) = Gamma(x) * Gamma(y) / Gamma(x + y)
        numerator = gamma_x * gamma_y
        denominator = gamma_sum
        
        if denominator.value == 0:
            return HyperMorphicNumber(mpc('inf'), self.phi, self.psi)
        
        beta_val = numerator / denominator
        return beta_val







c. Hypermorphic Bessel Function
The classical Bessel function of the first kind is defined as:
Jn(z)=âˆ‘k=0âˆž(âˆ’1)kk!â€‰Î“(n+k+1)(z2)2k+nJ_n(z) = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^k}{k! \, \Gamma(n + k + 1)} \left( \frac{z}{2} \right)^{2k + n}Jnâ€‹(z)=k=0âˆ‘âˆžâ€‹k!Î“(n+k+1)(âˆ’1)kâ€‹(2zâ€‹)2k+n
Hypermorphic Adaptation:
Jn,HM(z)=Jn(z)modâ€‰â€‰Ïˆ(current precision)J_{n,\text{HM}}(z) = J_n(z) \mod \psi(\text{current precision})Jn,HMâ€‹(z)=Jnâ€‹(z)modÏˆ(current precision)
